title: Hanover is district leader
text: Untitled Document Hanover is district leader Hanover quarterback Will Bruna is dragged down by Lincoln's Owen Krueger in the second quarter of a district and HHS homecoming game. Photo by Julie Perry Axtell has pivotal game Friday; Frankfort needs win Published: Wednesday, October 14, 2015 5:15 PM CDT No game is bigger than the next one and that’s true for Axtell, 5-1, which will meet eight-man Division II district leader and visitor Pike Valley in a 7 p.m. game Friday.The Eagles, who won 46-0 at Southern Cloud last week, are tied with Pike Valley and Linn at 2-0.In the district, Pike Valley has 42 points. Axtell has 27. Linn has 31. Points are the last thing used to break ties when it comes down to determining which teams will advance into the postseason. Head to head is the first decider. Frankfort, 0-2 after a 74-50 loss to Pike Valley, may have a tough time making the playoffs, but what the Wildcats do in the next three weeks could have an impact on the district outcome. The Cats play at 7 p.m. Friday against guest Linn, 2-4. In eight-man Division I, Hanover, 3-0, is No. 1 in the district with 63 points after a 58-12 homecoming win Friday against Lincoln, Kan. The state-ranked Wildcats are at winless Lakeside-Downs for a 7 p.m. district game Friday.“It is important that we continue to play with focus as we travel to take on Lakeside,” HHS coach Matt Heuer said. Axtell 46, Southern Cloud 0 The only run Axtell junior Burke Deters made was for a 61-yard touchdown in the third quarter that ended play at Southern Cloud.Axtell had a built a 40-0 lead by halftime from a 14-yard sophomore Kaleb Buessing pass to freshman Nate Buessing; Kaleb Buessing’s runs of 6 and 10 yards; Buessing 22-yard pass to senior Brice Koch and Nate Buessing’s 5-yard run.
